<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>What is Message Authentication Code? List the operation of computing digest value in different passes of MD4. Describe about Needhom-Schroeder protocol.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Message Authentication Code is a function of the message and a secret key that produce a fixed-length value that serves as the authenticator. This technique assumethat the sender has a message to send receiver it caculates the MAC as a function of message and key.</p>
<p>The MD4 function is a cryptographic algorithm that takes a message of srbitrary length as input and produce a 128-bit message digest or hash value as output<br />
Suppose a b-bit message as input and we need to find its message digest. It is assumed that the bits of the message are m<sub>0</sub>, m<sub>1</sub>, m<sub>2</sub>, &#8230;&#8230;.., m<sub>b-1</sub>.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Step-1 : Append padded bits</strong> :<br />
The message is padded so that its length is congurent to 448 modulo 512. A single &#8216;1&#8217; bit is appended so that the length in bits equals 448 modulo 512.<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-44091 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/md4.drawio.png?resize=322%2C28&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="322" height="28">(Message length + padded bits) % 512 = 448</li>
<li><strong>Step-2 : Append length</strong> :<br />
A 64-bit representation of b is appended to the result of the previous step. The resulting message has a length that is an exact multiple of 512 bits.<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44092 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/md4-2.drawio.png?resize=287%2C25&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="287" height="25">(Message length + padded bits + 64 bits) % 512 = 0</li>
<li><strong>Step-3 : Initialize MD buffer</strong> :<br />
A 4- word buffer (A, B, C, D) is used to compute the message digest. Here, each of A, B, C, D is 32-bit register. These are initialized to the following values in hexadecimal, low &#8211; order byte first:<br />
A : 01 23 45 67<br />
B : 89 ab cd ef<br />
C : fe dc  ba 98<br />
D : 76 54 32 10</li>
<li><strong>Step 4 : Process message in 16-word blocks</strong> :<br />
It contains three passes (rounds) with 16 steps or operation each. We first define three auxiliary functions that each takes as input three 32-bit words and produce as output one 32-bit word.<br />
Pass 1: F(x, y, z) = (x ∧ y)∨(¬x ∧ z)  (step 0 to 15)<br />
Pass 2: F(x, y, z) = (x ∧ y)∨(x ∧ z)∨(y ∧ z)  (step 16 to 31)<br />
Pass 3: F(x, y, z) = x⊕y⊕z  (step 32 to 47)</li>
<li><strong>Step 5 : Output</strong> :<br />
After all rounds have performed the buffer A, B, C, D contains the MD4 output starting with lower bit A and ending with higher bit D.</li>
</ul>
<p>Roger Needham and Michael Schroeder proposed the Needham-Schroeder protocol in 1978. It is a pair of cryptographic protocols that are used for safe authentication between two parties via a network. It is a shared key authentication protocol designed to generate and propagate a session key. It includes the Symmetric key protocol and asymmetric key protocol.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Symmetric key protocol establishes a session key to protect further communication.</li>
<li>Asymmetric key protocol provides mutual authentication between two parties communicating on a network.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Why do we need discrete logarithm? Illustrate with an example. Consider a Diffie-Hellman scheme with a common prime p = 13 between user A and user B. Suppose public key of A is 10 and public key of B is 8. Now determine their private keys and shared secret key. Select any valid primitive root of 13.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Discrete logarithms are vital in cryptography because of the discrete logarithm problem&#8217;s complexity. This complexity ensures that the public keys can be safely shared over insecure channels while keeping the private keys and shared secret secure, forming the foundation of many secure communication protocols.</p>
<p>Discrete logarithms play a crucial role in modern cryptography, particularly in securing communication protocols such as Diffie-Hellman key exchange, ElGamal encryption, and Digital Signature Algorithms (DSA). The security of these systems relies on the difficulty of solving the discrete logarithm problem.</p>
<p>Given the Diffie-Hellman scheme with the following information:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Common prime <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">p = 13</span></span></li>
<li>Public key of A, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">A<sub>pub </sub>= 10</span></span></li>
<li>Public key of B, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">B<sub>pub </sub>= 8</span></span></li>
<li>We need to determine their private keys and shared secret key using a valid primitive root of 13.</li>
</ul>
<h4><strong> Select a primitive root of 13</strong></h4>
<p>Primitive roots of 13 are integers that can generate all the numbers from 1 to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">p−1 = 12</span></span> using modular exponentiation. For <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">p = 13</span></span>, a known primitive root is <strong>2</strong>.</p>
<h4><strong>Determine Private Keys of A and B</strong></h4>
<p>The private keys of users A and B, denoted as <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aa</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b</span></span> respectively, are determined as follows:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>User A&#8217;s public key is calculated using the formula:<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">A<sub>pub </sub>= g<sup>a </sup>mod  p</span></span></span>where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">g = 2 </span></span>is the primitive root, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aa</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span> is A&#8217;s private key, and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">p = 13</span></span>.</li>
<li>User B&#8217;s public key is similarly calculated:<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">B<sub>pub </sub>= g<sup>b </sup>mod  p</span></span></span>where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span></span></span></span> is B&#8217;s private key.</li>
</ul>
<p>We need to find <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a</span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b</span></span> such that the equations hold.</p>
<h5>For A:</h5>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">10 = 2<sup>a </sup>mod  13</span></span></span></p>
<p>We test powers of 2 modulo 13 to find <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aa</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span>:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">2<sup>1 </sup>= 2, 2<sup>2 </sup>= 4, 2<sup>3 </sup>= 8, 2<sup>4 </sup>= 3, 2<sup>5 </sup>= 6, 2<sup>6 </sup>= 12, 2<sup>7 </sup>= 11, 2<sup>8 </sup>= 9, 2<sup>9 </sup>= 5, 2<sup>10 </sup>= 10</span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a = 10</span></span> satisfies the equation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">2<sup>10 </sup>mod  13 = 10</span></span>.</p>
<h5>For B:</h5>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">8 = 2<sup>b </sup>mod  13</span></span></span></p>
<p>Testing the same powers of 2 modulo 13:</p>
<p><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">2<sup>3 </sup>= 8</span></span></p>
<p>Thus, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b = 3</span></span> satisfies the equation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">2<sup>3 </sup>mod  13 = 8</span></span></p>
<h4><strong>Compute Shared Secret Key</strong></h4>
<p>The shared secret key <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K</span></span> is calculated by both A and B as follows:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>A computes <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K =  B<sub>a</sub><sup>pub</sup>mod  p</span></span></li>
<li>B computes <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K =  A<sub>b</sub><sup>pub</sup>mod  p</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>These should result in the same value.</p>
<h5>A&#8217;s computation:</h5>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K = 8<sup>10 </sup>mod  13</span></span></span></p>
<p>We break down the exponentiation:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">8<sup>2 </sup>= 64 ⇒ 64 mod  13 = 12<br />
</span></span></span><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">8<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">4 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mord">2<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">144 </span><span class="mrel">⇒ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">144 </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathrm">mod </span></span><span class="mord">13 </span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span><br />
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">8<sup>8 </sup>= 1<sup>2</sup> = 1 ⇒ 8<sup>10 </sup>= 1×12 = 12</span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K=12</span></span>.</p>
<h5>B&#8217;s computation:</h5>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K = 10<sup>3</sup>mod  13<br />
</span></span></span><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mord">0<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">100 </span><span class="mrel">⇒ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">100 </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathrm">mod </span></span><span class="mord">13 </span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">9</span></span></span></span></span><br />
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mord">0<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">3 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">10</span><span class="mbin">⋅</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">9 </span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">90 </span><span class="mrel">⇒</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">90 </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathrm">mod </span></span><span class="mord">13 </span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">12</span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K=12</span></span>.</p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Hence, The private keys are:</span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a=10</span></span> (for A)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b=3</span></span> (for B)</li>
</ul>
<p>The shared secret key is:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">K=12</span></span>.</li>
</ul>
<p>This shared secret key is now known only to users A and B, even though the exchange occurred over a public channel, thanks to the difficulty of solving the discrete logarithm problem.</p>
</div>
