<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Discuss the working mechanism of kerberos protocol.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The <strong>Kerberos authentication protocol</strong> is one that aids in user authentication prior to communication. It is an authentication system that safely confirms users&#8217; and services&#8217; identities over an insecure network using secret-key cryptography.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-43957 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Kerbrose.drawio.png?resize=507%2C196&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="507" height="196"></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">fig. Kerberos Authentication Protocol</p>
<p>The components of Kerberos are as follows:</p>
<p><strong>KDS</strong>: Key Distribution System is what KDS stands for. This is in charge of user authentication and ticket or key issuance. AS, or Authentication Service, and TGS, or Ticket Grant System, are the two components that make up KDS. The user is verified by the authentication service before being able to submit a ticket request. TGS offers both a scession and a ticket for interacting with the server.</p>
<p><strong>User</strong>: A user is an entity that attempts to access resources from another location and requires authorization to do so.</p>
<p><strong>Server</strong>: The location, organization, or source from which the user receives resources for usage is known as the server.</p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Working of Kerberos authentication protocol</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>User request KDS i.e Key Distribution System for access to the ticket from TGS.</li>
<li>KDS in response grants it the permission to access ticket from TGS, by authenticating it with help of AS.</li>
<li>User again request TGS i.e Ticket Grant System for a ticket to communicate with the server.</li>
<li>TGS grants a ticket and a session for the communication with the server.</li>
<li>User then request for the resource from the server in the particular session using the ticket.</li>
<li>Server recognizing the ticket grants the access to the resource for that particular session.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>What is the use of firewall? How circuit level gateway differs from stateful inspection firewall?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A “firewall”, is a tool that provides a filter of both incoming and outgoing packets. Thus, the use of the firewall is to monitor and control all incoming or outgoing access to network connections based on predetermined security rules. Most firewalls perform two basic use.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Packet filtering is based on accept or deny policy that is itself based on the rules of the security policy.</li>
<li>Application proxy gateways provide services to the inside users and at the same time protect each individual host from the “bad” outside users.</li>
</ul>
