<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>What is intrusion ? Explain any two types of intrusion detection system.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Intrusion are the set of action that on being performed harms the confidentiality, integrity, availability an security policy. The one who perform the action are usually unauthhorized and they try to access the data and information.<br />
It is any unapproved action, attack, or access to a computer system or network with the goal of stealing, destroying, or interfering with data and resources. From straightforward illegal access to complex attacks by malevolent individuals seeking to jeopardize system security, privacy, or integrity, intrusions can take many different forms.</p>
<h3>Types of Intrusion Detection Systems</h3>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Network-based Intrusion Detection System (NIDS)</strong>: In order to identify questionable activity occurring throughout the network, NIDS continuously analyzes network traffic. To examine incoming and outgoing packets, it is typically installed at particular network nodes, such gateways or routers.<br />
Both anomaly-based detection (finding departures from typical traffic patterns) and signature-based detection (matching patterns of known attack signatures) are used by NIDS.</li>
<li><strong>Host-based Intrusion Detection System (HIDS)</strong>: Individual hosts or devices have HIDS installed, which keeps an eye on things like user activity, system logs, and file integrity. It is intended to spot questionable activity on the particular device it is watching.<br />
HIDS frequently uses file integrity checks and log analysis to find any illegal changes, such as adjustments to system files or configuration settings.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Find the multiplicative inverse of polynomial {95} using extended euclidean Algorithm.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>We first compute ϕ(95), where ϕ stands for Euler&#8217;s Totient Function. In order to determine the multiplicative inverse of 95 we are here using its totient value. After obtaining ϕ(95), we may get the inverse of 95 modulo ϕ(95) using the Extended Euclidean Algorithm.</p>
<p>Since <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">95 = 5 × 19</span></span>, we can use the property of Euler’s Totient Function:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ϕ(95) = ϕ(5) × ϕ(19)</span></span></span></p>
<p>where:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ϕ(5) = 5 − 1 = 4 and ϕ(19) = 19 − 1 = 18</span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus,</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ϕ(95) = 4 × 18 = 72</span></span></span></p>
<p>now, we calculate the multiplicative inverse of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">95</span></span> modulo <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">72</span></span> using the Extended Euclidean Algorithm where x = x<sub>1</sub> &#8211; qx<sub>2</sub></p>
