<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What is DoS attack ? Discuss about PKI trust model.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>When coordinated from multiple sources, it is known as a Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack. A Denial of Service (DoS) attack is a type of cyberattack that aim to disrupt the normal functioning of a targeted server, network, or service by flooding it with a flood of illegitimate requests, exhausting the resources (e.g., bandwidth, memory, CPU) of the target system, rendering it unavailable to legitimate users.</p>
<p><strong>Important Features of DoS Attacks</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Resource Exhaustion: To deplete the target&#8217;s resources, the attacker bombards it with requests.</li>
<li>Network Disruption: An attack can affect not only one server but the entire network.</li>
<li>Service Unavailability: Causes downtime and prevents authorized users from accessing services.</li>
</ul>
<p>Digital keys and certificates that protect data exchanges and identity verification in online settings are managed by the <strong>Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) architecture</strong>. To provide safe communication and authentication, the PKI trust model creates a network of connections and trust between things (such people, gadgets, and organizations).</p>
<p>The validity of digital certificates and secure communication are guaranteed by a PKI trust model, which establishes the connections between the various components of a security system. Unlike the Web of Trust architecture, which offers decentralized, peer-based validation, the hierarchical approach offers centralized, widely trusted administration. Every model takes certain organizational and security requirements into account.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Using Vignere cipher with key = “worlds”, encrypt the plain text “hello everyone”.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>given,</p>
<p>key = &#8220;worlds&#8221;</p>
<p>plain text = &#8220;hello everyone&#8221;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-43974" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/vig.drawio.png?resize=1681%2C1141&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="1681" height="1141"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">W O R L D S W O R L D S W<br />
H E L L O E V E R Y O N E</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">D S C W R W R S I J R F A</p>
<p>Hence the encrypted text is DSCWRWRSIJRFA.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe the different modes of block cipher.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Modes of Block Cipher Encryptions</strong> :</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Electronic Code Book</strong> : It is the simplest mode in which plaintext is handled one block at a time and each block of plain text is encrpted using the same key. The term codebook is used because, for a given key, there is a unique ciphertext for every b-bit block of plaintext.<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44061 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ECB.jpg?resize=228%2C181&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="228" height="181"></li>
<li><strong>Cipher Block Chaining Mode</strong> : In this technique, the input to the encryption algorithm is the XOR of the current plaintext block and the preceeding ciphertext block; the same key is used for each block. In effect, we have chained together the processing of the sequence of the plaintext blocks.<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44062 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/CBC.drawio.png?resize=252%2C238&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="252" height="238"></li>
<li><strong>Cipher Feedback Mode</strong> : In this mode, each cipher text block gets feedback into the encryption process, inorder to encrypt the next plaintext block. The CFB mode requiresan iniialization vector (IV) as the initial random b bir block.<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44065 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/CFM.drawio.png?resize=252%2C161&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="252" height="161"></li>
<li><strong>Output Feedback Mode</strong> : The output feedback mode (OFB) is similar in structure to that of CFB. The only difference is that the output of the encryption function that is fed back to the shift register in OFB, where in CFB the ciphertext unit is fed back to the shift register.<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44066 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/OFM.drawio.png?resize=238%2C152&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="238" height="152"></li>
<li><strong>Counter Mode</strong> : A counter equal to the plaintext blocksize is used in this mode. The counter is initialized to some value and then increment by 1 for each block. The counter is encrypted with the key K and XOR the output of the plaintext block to produce the cipher text block.<br />
<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44073 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/counter.drawio.png?resize=180%2C166&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="180" height="166"></li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on (any two)</p>
<ol>
<li>Totient value of any positive integer.</li>
<li>Properties of hash function.</li>
<li>Virus or Worms.</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Totient value of any positive integer</strong></span>: It is defined as the number of positive integer less than n, which are relatively prime to n. It is denoted by Φ(n).<br />
If n is the prime number then, Φ(n) = n-1.for eg: Φ(10) = ?<br />
Number less than 10 are {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9}<br />
now,<br />
Number relatively prime to 10 are {1, 3, 7, 9}<br />
Φ(10) =4</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Properties of hash function</strong></span> : It is a function that maps a message of any length into a fixed length hash value, which serves as an authenticator. Its properties are:<br />
<strong>i.</strong> One way i.e a hash code can be generated from the message but a message can&#8217;t be extracted from the code.<br />
<strong>ii.</strong> Strong collision resistence i.e for any input m<sub>1</sub>, it is computationally hard to find a different input m<sub>2</sub> such that H(m<sub>1</sub>)=H(m<sub>2</sub>).<br />
<strong>iii.</strong> A message m<sub>1</sub> will have same hash code as m<sub>2 </sub>i.e H(m<sub>1</sub>)=H(m<sub>2</sub>) when m<sub>1</sub> = m<sub>2 </sub>.<br />
<strong>iv.</strong> It produce a fixed length output for any length input.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Virus or Worms</strong></span>:<br />
